  "opinion": "As a woman in my late fifties who grew up in a household where both parents were academics, I’ve witnessed firsthand how the gender gap in science isn’t just a statistic—it’s a lived experience. My parents’ PhDs gave me early exposure to the world of ideas, but their professions also shaped my understanding of what science *really* means. Growing up in Rome with a background that’s steeped in intellectual curiosity yet limited by the practical realities of my own education—only lower secondary—has taught me that the gender gap in science is less about innate ability and more about systemic barriers that whisper rather than shout. For instance, when I volunteered at a local science outreach program for children, I noticed how many girls hesitated to ask questions in group settings, not because they lacked interest, but because they felt their curiosity was dismissed as 'too childish.' This is the gap: a quiet erosion of confidence that starts early and deepens over time. Addressing it isn’t about grand gestures—it’s about creating spaces where girls feel safe to ask 'why' without fear of judgment. In my community, this means supporting mentors who model curiosity without gendered expectations, ensuring that science is presented as a journey of discovery, not a competition. I’ve seen it in my own garden—where the act of nurturing plants teaches patience and observation, mirroring the slow, deliberate process of scientific inquiry. The solution lies in small, consistent actions: teacher training that includes gender-inclusive language, after-school clubs that welcome all children regardless of gender, and parents who encourage questioning without shame. We must stop treating the gender gap as a problem to be fixed by a single solution and start seeing it as a reflection of how we value curiosity in our communities. It’s time to let science thrive for everyone, not just those who fit a narrow mold.",
